<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>GMC submission to the Health Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from General Medical Council</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (GMC0002)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About the GMC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The General Medical Council is the independent regulator of doctors in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We are accountable to Parliament.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our job is to protect, promote and maintain the health and safety of the public by ensuring proper standards in the practice of medicine. We do this by: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">managing entry to the medical register (there are currently 250,000 doctors on the register)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">setting the educational standards for all UK doctors through medical schools and postgraduate education and training</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">determining the principles and values that underpin good medical practice </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">taking firm but fair action where those standards have not been met.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Health Select Committee’s 2012 report on the GMC concluded that we are an effective regulator. The Committee also made several recommendations that we are committed to taking forward in order to improve the way we protect patients. Here we set out the progress we have made across a range of areas since our last accountability report. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also explain how we are responding to the recommendations in the Francis report that are related to our work. A more detailed report on this, including our response to the Berwick review of patient safety and the Keogh review of 14 trusts with high mortality rates, is available on our website: </span><a href="http://www.gmc-uk.org/about/23442.asp"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gmc-uk.org/about/23442.asp</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Revalidation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Implementation and evaluation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since revalidation started in December 2012 – with the support of the UK Government, the devolved administrations and the Health Select Committee – we have revalidated more than 20,000 doctors. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are on track to revalidate the vast majority of licensed doctors in the UK for the first time by March 2016. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">86% of doctors in the UK are now linked to organisations that can support them with revalidation. And we have established a route to revalidation for doctors without a designated body. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2,300</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> doctors who have not yet responded to our requests to provide information for their revalidation have received final notice letters advising them that if they fail to respond we will have to take steps to remove their licence to practise. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Of these, 1,260 are registered as having an overseas address.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have developed a guide on e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ffective clinical governance to help b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oards and governing bodies assess if their organisations have systems in place that are sufficiently robust to support quality patient care and revalidation. This handbook was produced in partnership with the CQC, Monitor, Healthcare Improvement Scotland, Healthcare Inspectorate Wales and Northern Ireland’s Regulation and Quality Improvement Authority as well as the Government Procurement Service. It stresses the importance of organisations creating environments which foster and assure good professional practice and the role revalidation can play within that - an issue highlighted by the Francis Report. We will write to the Chair of every designated healthcare organisation in the UK drawing attention to the importance of revalidation as a means of promoting patient safety and underlining the responsibility of Boards to ensure they have robust systems of clinical governance to underpin the revalidation process. Jointly with our partners we will continue to promote this message to healthcare organisations.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Committee’s last report on the GMC emphasised the importance of ensuring that revalidation is effectively managed and rigorously monitored. We agree and have launched a major project to monitor the implementation of revalidation to assess and evaluate its impact on employers, doctors and patients. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To begin evaluating the impact of revalidation we have commissioned a team from Plymouth University Peninsula Schools of Medicine and Dentistry to help us develop an evaluation framework, taking into account the perspectives of doctors, employers and patients' groups. We will then commission a third party to start collecting data for the subsequent evaluation in the new year.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Patient feedback </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Health Select Committee called on us to consider setting more challenging targets which will ensure doctors regularly seek and reflect on their patients’ views. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patient feedback is one of six types of supporting information that a doctor must collect for revalidation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at least once in every revalidation cycle, usually every five years. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Doctors need to review this feedback with their appraiser, reflect and act on what it says about their practice and performance. Doctors are also expected to bring a review of complaints and compliments they have received from patients to their annual appraisal.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Revalidation is a significant first step in ensuring that all doctors reflect on patient feedback; we are conscious however that more can be done to ensure patient views are regularly sought and reflected upon and we will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">keep this aspect of revalidation under review</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. As part of our evaluation of revalidation we will examine the frequency and the methods doctors use to obtain patient feedback. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We will also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">continue to work with patient organisations to raise awareness of revalidation and the role patients can play in providing feedback.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Registration</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Considerable progress has been made since our last accountability hearing towards ensuring doctors working in the UK have the necessary knowledge of English to practise safely.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since April 2013, Responsible Officers in England have had a duty to ensure that the doctors for whom they are responsible have sufficient knowledge of English. We are working with NHS Employers and others to ensure they are aware of and understand their duties in this area.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Department of Health has agreed to put proposals to parliament to amend the Medical Act next year which will allow us to check the language skills of doctors from the European Economic Area after the point of registration but before granting a licence to practise. The Department of Health and the GMC are currently consulting on these proposals which would allow us to do so in cases where we have concerns about a doctor’s knowledge of English.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are pleased that following engagement from the GMC and other regulators in Europe the new directive will now contain significant improvements which will enhance patient safety. In particular the revised text of the Recognition of Professional Qualifications Directive now states that competent authorities - such as the GMC - should have explicit powers to assess the language competency of all health professionals after their qualifications have been recognised but before they are allowed to practise. The new Directive will need to be transposed into UK law by the end of 2015. At this point the GMC should be able to introduce a more comprehensive scheme for language controls before doctors are given a licence to practise in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We will also continue to work with the UK Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Department of Health, the European Union institutions, and other UK and overseas regulators on the implementation of the new Directive.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Promoting professional standards </span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Committee’s last report on the GMC commended the steps we have taken to help doctors understand their professional obligations and recommended that we continue to pursue this. We regard this as an important strand of our work and have significantly increased our efforts in this area over the past year.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Raising standards</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In March 2013 we launched a new edition of our core guidance for all doctors. Shorter and updated, the new version of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Good medical practice, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">underpins all our professional and educational standards as well as Revalidation. A copy of the new guidance has been sent to every doctor in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">For the first time in our history we have also produced a guide for patients, based on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Good medical practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> This sets out what patients can expect from their doctor and what they can do if those standards are not met. It has proved very popular and we will continue to promote the guide in our work at local level. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">We are also w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">orking as part of NHS England’s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Leadership Alliance for the Care of Dying People</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> lead and provide a focus for improving the care for these patients and their families in response to the recommendations made in the report on the Liverpool Care Pathway </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">led by Baroness Neuberger.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In order to promote our guidance on professional standards , our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Employer Liaison Service, Regional Liaison Service and offices in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales have engaged with employers, patient groups throughout the country as well as with every UK medical school and, up to October with more than 12,000 doctors.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are also piloting a programme for doctors new to practice in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to provide them with a greater understanding of the ethical and professional standards expected of them. 300 doctors new to practice in the UK have attended one of the eleven events we have delivered across the UK. We have also delivered components of this programme at other induction events organised by educators and employers as well as developed an on-line self-assessment system for those who cannot access the face to face training sessions. We are currently looking at whether there are ways in which we can roll this out so that it is available to all doctors new to UK practice. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Raising concerns about patient safety</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An open learning and reporting culture is fundamental for patient safety and key to driving up professional standards. This has been underlined by the Francis Report, the Berwick Report and previous reports by the Health Select Committee.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since our last appearance before the Committee we have launched two new services to help doctors recognise and fulfil their obligations in this area: </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In December 2012 we launched a confidential helpline for doctors who wish to seek advice or raise concerns when they feel unable to do this locally. After initial assessment, these calls may either be investigated by the GMC or referred to other organisations, such as the CQC. In less than a year we have received in excess of 850 calls leading to 64 investigations into allegations which suggest that a doctor may not be fit to practise.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  We have also launched an online tool which provides practical help for doctors in deciding how and where they should report concerns about patient safety. </span></li></ul><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In addition to these new services, we continue to use our annual National Training Survey to ask all 50,000 doctors in training to inform us of any concerns they may have about patient safety in their training environment. This year, more than o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">ne in twenty doctors in training responded with a patient safety concern. Every one </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">of those concerns has been reviewed and shared with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">deaneries and local education training boards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> so they can be investigated. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">They then report back to us, in deans’ reports, to state whether they were able to verify the concern and to share their action plans. We monitor the local action and improvement being taken for any new and confirmed issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Fitness to Practise</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Speeding up the time it takes to conclude cases</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have acted on the Committee’s recommendation to set a target of closing 90% of all complaints within 12 months of receipt. We have agreed this following a review of our Key Performance Indicators and started to report on this from September 2013. We have met this target in September and October.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While we are closing 90% of all cases received within 12 months, complicated cases that require a hearing take longer. For example, where we are waiting for the outcome of criminal investigations and legal proceedings.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have an on-going programme of improvements to ensure our processes remain fit for purpose. Some of the improvements include:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the launch of a new online complaint form, which makes it easier for complainants to provide the right information at the right time.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  improvements to the information we provide to complainants and referring organisations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  improvements to the way we monitor and track individual cases</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 57.05pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  the development of a new process for handling complaints which would be more appropriately dealt with at a local level. </span></li></ul><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These initiatives and the wider reforms that we are taking forward, including the roll-out of the Employer Liaison Service and our pilots of meetings with doctors and complainants during an investigation, should result in an improved and in many cases a quicker process for dealing with complaints.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Medical Practitioners Tribunal Service (MPTS)</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The operationally separate MPTS began work in June 2012, and has made independent decisions in more than 3,000 Interim Order Panel hearings and more than 500 Fitness to Practise hearings.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">New medical panellists began sitting in early 2013 and the MPTS is in the process of recruiting new lay panellists. Panellists are expected to demonstrate integrity and objectivity and the current recruitment is encouraging applications from candidates with legal qualifications. The aim is to use more legally qualified chairs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who will be able to take a more active in case management, ensuring that time is not wasted by any of the parties involved.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The MPTS Chair, His Honour David Pearl, is pursuing a programme of reform to create a modern, efficient adjudication service. Changes to the Fitness to Practise Rules enacted in May 2013 allowed improvements to how hearings are run, with witness statements accepted as ‘evidence-in-chief’, greater use of video evidence and clarification of rules of evidence.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The MPTS (and the GMC) supports a new power for panels to award costs against either party (GMC or doctor) if they behave unreasonably in the conduct of proceedings. The Department of Health has indicated that it will consult on this and other major reforms in 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Right of appeal</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Committee have in previous reports recommended that the Government should introduce legislation that would enable the GMC to appeal MPTS panel decisions. The Department of Health has agreed to this in principle and we are continuing to work with officials with a view to achieving reform in 2014.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Understanding complaints about doctors</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We received 8,109 complaints in 2012. This represents an increase of 24% on 2011 and 104% since 2007.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are likely to be a number of factors driving this rise in complaints and in the past we have surveyed medical directors to identify the reasons for the rising number of referrals from them. We have this year commissioned further research to look into the increase in complaints from the public and we will publish the findings shortly.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In October we published our annual report on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">State of Medical Education and Practice in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. This report presents a profile of the medical profession in 2012, and looks at major trends and identifies some of the challenges facing doctors, educators and employers. The report is available on our website: </span><a href="http://www.gmc-uk.org/publications/23435.asp"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.gmc-uk.org/publications/23435.asp</span></a></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Education</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are undertaking a comprehensive review of the way we quality assure medical education (including training environments) and will publish our proposals in the first half of 2014. This work includes consideration of recommendations in the Francis Report on the education and training of doctors. Among other things, we are looking at how we can work more closely with the medical Royal Colleges. In the meantime, we are making our work more visible and accessible to the public (see for example, our July 2013 report on Emergency Medicine training). We plan to publish details of services where we have concerns about the education of doctors. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Subject to discussion by our Council and decisions on implementation by the four UK health departments, we are committed to taking forward the recommendations in the independent review of postgraduate medical training led by Professor David Greenaway which was published in October 2013, to make sure that UK doctors have the right knowledge and skills to meet patients’ needs in the years to come.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Working with our key partners</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC, other professional regulators, the CQC, medical royal colleges, employers and educators are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">part of a wider system that needs to be focussed on improving the quality and safety of care. The Francis Report set a clear challenge that we should work more closely together and we are determined to do so.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Building on our Memorandum of Understanding with the CQC, we have put in place detailed practical arrangements to protect patients and share information more effectively. We have put in place a joint operational protocol which sets out key contacts at both organisations and in practical terms when and how we will share our information with each other. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have already seen a significant increase in the flow of information between the two organisations and we are committed to build on this - currently we share our complaints information, hearing decisions, revalidation decisions and National Training Survey data.  Similarly, the CQC shares information with us which informs our investigations and work in assuring the quality of medical education. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We provided information from our fitness to practise and education work to the Keogh review of 14 trusts with high mortality rates. The report of this review expressed an ambition that we continue to share this information with the CQC and others and we are committed to doing so.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In addition, we sit on the National Quality Board and work with the new Quality Surveillance Groups to share intelligence and agree how we can best work together where we believe patient safety may be at risk. This represents a departure from the traditional way in which professional regulators have engaged with the system – we have moved from being almost entirely reactive, to seeking ways in which we can support wider safety initiatives. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We recognise that we work in a contentious area but believe that we have made good progress in the past year – we are committed to reforming every part of our business to continue to improve the way we help protect patients and promote good medical practice. There is  much still to be done and we will continue to reflect on how we can take forward recommendations from the Health Select Committee as well those in the Francis Report and other subsequent reviews.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We expect 2014 to be an important year for the GMC. We will publish our new Corporate Strategy for 2014-17, which will shape the future direction of our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">work. We also expect the Government to introduce to Parliament a proposed new legal framework for the GMC and other professional regulators. This Bill, currently being developed by the Law Commission, offers an opportunity to address a number of issues that require legislative change. At the same time it will provide an opportunity for Parliament to discuss its expectations of professional healthcare regulation in the future.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>